Two Sum — Interview Simulation:

[CLARIFY]
'So I need to find two numbers in the array that add up to the target and return their indices.
A few questions: Can there be duplicate values? Can the same element be used twice? 
Is there always exactly one solution? Ok, assuming exactly one solution, no self-use.'

[APPROACH]
'I'll use a HashMap: for each element, I'll check if its complement (target - nums[i])
already exists in the map. If yes, return [map.get(complement), i].
If not, add nums[i] → i to the map.
This is O(n) time and O(n) space. One pass.'

[CODE]
import java.util.*;
public class TwoSum {
    public static int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {
        Map<Integer,Integer> seen = new HashMap<>(); // val → index
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            int complement = target - nums[i];
            if (seen.containsKey(complement))
                return new int[]{seen.get(complement), i};
            seen.put(nums[i], i);
        }
        return new int[]{};
    }
}

[TEST ALOUD]
'Input [2,7,11,15], target 9:
i=0: complement=7, not in map. Add 2→0.
i=1: complement=2, found at map[2]=0. Return [0,1]. Correct!'

[COMPLEXITY]
'O(n) time — one pass. O(n) space — HashMap stores n entries worst case.'

