Live Optimization — Pairs with Sum K:

[BRUTE FORCE O(n²)]
'Starting simple: for every pair i,j check if nums[i]+nums[j]==k.
That's O(n²) — nested loops.'

public static int countPairs(int[] nums, int k) {
    int count = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++)
        for (int j = i+1; j < nums.length; j++)
            if (nums[i] + nums[j] == k) count++;
    return count;
}

[OPTIMIZE — recognize the pattern]
'The bottleneck is the inner loop: we're checking if complement exists.
If we pre-store all values in a HashMap, we can do this lookup in O(1).'

[O(n) SOLUTION]
public static int countPairsOptimal(int[] nums, int k) {
    Map<Integer,Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
    for (int n : nums) freq.merge(n, 1, Integer::sum);
    int count = 0;
    for (int n : nums) {
        int complement = k - n;
        count += freq.getOrDefault(complement, 0);
        if (complement == n) count--; // subtract self-pairing
    }
    return count / 2; // each pair counted twice
}

[COMPLEXITY COMPARISON]
'Brute force: O(n²) time O(1) space.
Optimized: O(n) time O(n) space.
Trade-off: we use O(n) extra memory to save O(n²) → O(n) time.'

